— Kenneth Noland (1910-2003)
Kenneth Noland (1910-2003) was an American abstract expressionist painter, sculptor, and graphic designer. He was born in Baltimore, Maryland, and died in New York City. Noland studied painting at the University of Maryland and then at the Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Arts. He moved to New York in 1939, where he worked for the Art Students League and the Society of Landscape Artists. In 1946, Noland was a founding member of the New York School of Abstract Painting, which included artists such as Adolph Gottlieb, Franz Kline, and Philip Guston. Noland's paintings are characterized by their bright colors, bold lines, and geometric shapes. He often used color to create a sense of movement and energy in his work. Noland also experimented with different materials, including metal, wood, and fabric, to create his sculptures and installations. In 1964, Noland received the prestigious Pollock-Krasner Foundation Award, and in 1996, he was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by President Bill Clinton. Noland's work is held in numerous museums and collections, including the Museum of Modern Art

“Demographics are destiny,” said James P. Smith, a professor of public policy at Harvard University, in a lecture last week at the Center for American Progress. “Demographics are destiny” because, he said, “the number and distribution of people of different racial and ethnic backgrounds, as well as the attitudes, values, and behaviors of those people, affect everything from what kinds of jobs are available to what kinds of health care is provided to what kinds of educational opportunities are available to what kinds of communities are formed, and so on.”
